.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:8:2. The `SessionState` type in `session-state.ts` is deliberately lightweight: `sessionId`, `activeGoal`, `seenResultIds`, `openQuestions`, `preferredAnchors`, `createdAt`, and `updatedAt`. `getOrCreate()` creates it lazily, `updateGoal()` changes focus, `markSeen()` accumulates seen memory IDs, and the manager evicts by inactivity TTL plus LRU capacity. ([session-state.ts:34](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-state.ts#L34), [session-state.ts:83](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-state.ts#L83), [session-state.ts:118](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-state.ts#L118), [session-state.ts:191](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-state.ts#L191))
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:10:3. Session IDs are server-minted and server-trusted. If a caller omits `sessionId`, `resolveTrustedSession()` generates a UUID and treats it as the `effectiveSessionId`. If a caller supplies one, it must already be tracked and identity-bound, or the server rejects it. `memory_context` then passes only `effectiveSessionId` downstream and exposes it in response metadata. ([session-manager.ts:385](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/session/session-manager.ts#L385), [session-manager.ts:396](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/session/session-manager.ts#L396), [session-manager.ts:401](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/session/session-manager.ts#L401), [memory-context.ts:1060](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-context.ts#L1060), [memory-context.ts:955](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-context.ts#L955))
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:14:5. `session-boost.ts` does not boost “recent sessions”; it boosts memories that already have attention inside the current session’s `working_memory`. It reads `attention_score` for matching `memory_id`s, converts that to a boost with multiplier `0.15`, caps combined session+causal boost at `0.20`, multiplies the current ranking score, clamps to `[0,1]`, preserves the original `attentionScore`, and re-sorts. This only runs in hybrid search when `config.sessionId` is present. ([session-boost.ts:8](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-boost.ts#L8), [session-boost.ts:64](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-boost.ts#L64), [session-boost.ts:87](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-boost.ts#L87), [session-boost.ts:129](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-boost.ts#L129), [session-boost.ts:168](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/session-boost.ts#L168), [stage2-fusion.ts:738](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/pipeline/stage2-fusion.ts#L738))
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:18:7. The bridge rule for `hook-state.ts` should be: never pass Claude’s raw `session_id` into Spec Kit as `sessionId`. That value is not trusted unless the server already minted and tracks it. The hook should store a local mapping `claudeSessionId -> effectiveSessionId`, mint the Spec Kit ID via `memory_context` on first contact, and reuse only the returned `effectiveSessionId` afterward. `memory_match_triggers` already documents this contract in its recovery hint. This is an inference from the trust model, but it is strongly implied by the server’s validation path. ([session-manager.ts:401](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/session/session-manager.ts#L401), [memory-context.ts:1049](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-context.ts#L1049), [memory-context.ts:1056](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-context.ts#L1056), [memory-triggers.ts:207](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-triggers.ts#L207), [memory-triggers.ts:225](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Opencode%20Env/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-triggers.ts#L225))
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:34:The highest-value new information is that the bridge cannot treat Claude’s `session_id` as the Spec Kit session key. The MCP server has a trust boundary around `effectiveSessionId`, and lifecycle recovery is DB-backed in `session-manager.ts`, not in `session-state.ts`. That means `hook-state.ts` needs a mapping/cache layer, not just a thin pass-through wrapper.
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-020.md:42:- On first use, call `memory_context` without `sessionId`, read back `sessionLifecycle.effectiveSessionId`, and persist the mapping. Never send raw Claude `session_id` into MCP tools.
